news.title: Faster Wi-Fi 6 in Thomson Medical
news.content: Singtel has deployed Wi-Fi 6 hotspots at Thomson Medical. Users with Wi-Fi 6 compatible devices can enjoy a faster connection speed.

news.title: New Wireless@SGx operator: SIMBA
news.content: SIMBA is now a Wireless@SG operator! SIMBA users can now log on to Wireless@SG and enjoy FREE WiFi Internet access in public places across Singapore.

qs.q: I have run the WOLS app and completed the setup, but why can't I connect to the Internet?
qs.a: If you have an existing Wireless@SGx connection, network profile or saved network, you may need to delete or remove them before running the setup to avoid erroneous duplicate network entries.

qs.q: Can I use a foreign mobile phone number for registering a user account in the WOLS App to connect to Wireless@SGx?
qs.a: Foreign mobile phone numbers are not supported at the moment by WOLS App. The country code option in the registration page is locked to Singapore only.

qs.q: Can foreign visitors connect to Wireless@SGx using their foreign mobile phone numbers?
qs.a: Foreign mobile phone numbers are not supported at the moment by WOLS App. The country code option in the registration page is locked to Singapore only. However, foreign visitors can use the official Wireless@SGx App that supports foreign phone numbers to register instead. The official App however, runs on Windows, macOS, Android and iOS only; there is no Linux support.

qs.q: The system did not send me an OTP during registration. What can I do?
qs.a: Check that your mobile device is not in airplane mode and is connected to your telco network. Mobile/cellular charges may apply for receiving the OTP SMS. Your mobile/cellular operator may assist you with SMS-related issues.

qs.q: How does Wireless@SGx use EAP-SIM? Does my device support EAP-SIM?
qs.a: Wireless@SGx accepts EAP-SIM login mechanism and is supported by most mobile devices. While local SIM cards support EAP-SIM login by default, Singtel pre-paid users are required to activate their SIM card for Wireless@SGx SIM login by dialing *360. When in doubt, you may check your device's manual for EAP-SIM support.

qs.q: Why is a configuration file necessary for iOS devices? How can I be sure if the configuration file is authentic?
qs.a: A specially-installed iOS device configuration file is required for security. This locks your device to known legitimate Wireless@SGx hotspots only.

qs.q: Is EAP-SIM available on all Android devices?
qs.a: While most Android devices today support EAP-SIM by default, however, they are customised by their manufacturers and support is not guaranteed and should not be assumed.

qs.q: How do I connect to Wireless@SGx on my Linux laptop?
qs.a: Users can connect to Wireless@SGx on their Linux laptops by using the WOLS App (shameless plug) and going through the one-time setup process. Alternatively, for most modern Linux distributions, they can use the GNOME Network Manager or nmcli command to create the Saved network connection. Some older distributions without GNOME Desktop may need to edit the wpa-supplicant configuration instead.

qs.q: How long is my Wireless@SGx account valid for?
qs.a: For non-SIM setup, the account is valid for 12 months, and users are required to re-register upon expiry. For EAP-SIM, it is based on the SIM card's validity.

qs.q: Can I register an account with any telco operator, connect to any telco's hotspots with any SIM card?
qs.a: Yes, users are free to register with and connect to any Wireless@SG operator. There is no requirement to register or connect with the same telco as your SIM card/mobile line.

qs.q: Where are the Wireless@SGx's hotspots?
qs.a: You can find a list of Wireless@SG hotspots on IMDA webpage, and in the WOLS App plotted on a map.

qs.q: Is Wireless@SGx usage unlimited?
qs.a: Yes. Just reconnect if you are disconnected.

qs.q: Can businesses use Wireless@SGx for commercial or corporate purposes?
qs.a: Contact your telco for more information on Wireless@SG enterprise services.

qs.q: Can users have multiple concurrent connections?
qs.a: Yes, users may connect with multiple devices simultaneously.

qs.q: What can I do in the event of limited, intermittent or no connectivity?
qs.a: Please check your Wi-Fi signal strength as a rough indication of connection quality. Moving closer to a hotspot can improve connection stability and access speed.

qs.q: Why am I disconnected?
qs.a: Idle connections are dropped after a period of inactivity to reduce network congestion.

qs.q: Who can I contact regarding connectivity problems?
qs.a: Connecting to Wireless@SGx on Linux is **NOT** officially supported. Please DO NOT contact any operator or IMDA for assistance if you are experiencing problems. Alternatively, you can still contact a telco provider, email INFO@imda.gov.sg or call IMDA at 6377 3800 but never ever tell them you are having problems while running on Linux.

qs.q: I can browse the Web but I cannot send or receive any email.
qs.a: Wireless@SGx does not support SMTP authentication, which your email service may require. Use a web-based email service.

qs.q: I am using my SIM card for EAP-SIM login. How can I prevent illegitimate access should I ever lose my mobile device/SIM card?
qs.a: Notify your mobile service provider at the earliest opportunity to disable your lost/missing SIM card, and make a police report if your device is stolen.

qs.q: What should I do if I lose a device with non-SIM auto login enabled?
qs.a: Contact the relevant Wireless@SG operator to deactivate your Wireless@SGx account. You can find their contact information in the Contact Us page. Make a police report if your device is stolen.

qs.q: How do I protect myself while using Wireless@SGx?
qs.a: Please ensure the firewall, anti-virus, spam/ad blocker and virtual private networking (VPN) software are active and running on your devices. Exercise caution and common sense when browsing webpages, checking emails, and performing online transactions etc.

qs.q: Is Wireless@SGx safe for use?
qs.a: The Wireless@SGx network uses WPA2-Enterprise authentication and data encryption to protect your network traffic. You may wish to consider using a virtual private network (VPN) to further enhance your security.

qs.q: How can I tell if the Wi-Fi network is legit or real?
qs.a: Always connect only to an authenticated Wireless@SGx network (with a lock icon indicator).

qs.q: I completed the setup steps using the WOLS App on my Linux system. Why is it not connecting automatically?
qs.a: Please remove any prior Wireless@SGx network configuration before proceeding to the app setup. For GNOME desktop, click on Settings > Wi-Fi > Visible Networks > ... > Known Wi-Fi Networks / Saved Networks > Wireless@SGx, click the Gear icon, and check if the "Connect automatically" checkbox is selected.

qs.q: Which operating systems does WOLS support?
qs.a: The WOLS App is designed for Linux only. For iOS, Android, macOS and Windows, please use the official Wireless@SGx App from IMDA.

qs.q: How do I uninstall WOLS App?
qs.a: Just delete the directory it is extracted to. And the ~/.wols directory in home directory.

qs.q: Can I use WOLS App when I am not in a Wireless@SGx hotspot?
qs.a: You would need to register and set up your Wireless@SGx profile using a **working Internet connection** before you can join a Wireless@SGx hotspot. If you use a tethered connection on your phone for the setup, do note that you may incur data charges from your telco/ISP.

qs.q: Can I manually set up my Linux device to connect to Wireless@SGx without using WOLS App?
qs.a: Certainly. There is also the excellent wasg-register.py by Zerotypic (https://github.com/zerotypic/wasg-register) if you prefer a terminal-based Python app. And you may configure it manually using the GNOME Wi-Fi setting, nmcli command or editing the wpa-supplicant configuration.

qs.q: How can I access the Wireless@SGx network if this useless WOLS App works only on Linux?
qs.a: The official Wireless@SGx App is currently supported on 4 platforms/operating systems, namely iOS, Android, Windows and MacOS. Use it.

qs.q: I am using a Linux/ChromeOS device, how can I connect to Wireless@SGx?
qs.a: WOLS and wasg-register.py work on Linux, or you can perform a manual configuration if you know how to. ChromeOS? No idea.

qs.q: Do I need the WOLS App to login each time to Wireless@SGx?
qs.a: No it is not required. You can delete the App once the setup (Saved network/Connection) is done, until you need to re-register again after 12 months.

qs.q: What is WOLS App? What benefits do the WOLS App brings to Linux users?
qs.a: The WOLS App provides a user-friendly GUI to configure a Linux laptop to connect to Wireless@SGx with tested working configuration settings. Less sophisticated Linux users may appreciate that with this App, they do not have to discover the correct Wi-Fi settings through exhaustive trial-and-error experiments, or analyse how to obtain the log-in credentials. Like the official Wireless@SGx App counterpart, the WOLS App also provides additional features such as hotspot location finder, speed test, network diagnostis and useful contact information.

qs.q: If I uninstall the WOLS App, can I still log in to Wireless@SGx?
qs.a: Users are free to install,  uninstall and re-install the application as and when they want. Wireless@SGx will continue to work as long as the account has not expired, and the Wi-Fi configuration settings are correct.

qs.q: Should older versions of WOLS App be deleted?
qs.a: Just do it.
